<TITLE> CHT Regional Council wants total troops withdrawal deadline </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 07 (bdnews24.com)Chittagong Hill Tracts Regional Council chairman Santu Larma has called the government to set a deadline for complete troops pullout as the army started partial withdrawal from the hills region on Friday. "Chittagong Hill Tracts is still under army rule though 38 years passed after independence," he said at a discussion in Dhaka, in an echo of statement on Wednesday when he had asked the government to immediately declare a roadmap for the full implementation of the CHT Peace Accord. He had also said the army reigned supreme in the CHT was even after the recent announcemenet of the withdrawal of one brigade. Bangladesh Adivashi Forum organised the discussion at the National Press Club to mark the International Day of the World's Indigenous People on Sunday. "Indigenous people in the region are living in the hilly regions amid severe uncertainties as the army drive is going on there," Larma, former Shantibahini militia chief, alleged. "How long will it go on?" Workers Party president Rashed Khan Menon MP and Jatiya Samajtantrik Dal president Hasanul Haq Inu also called for the total recall of the army from the tracts immediately. Among others, Bangladesh Adivashi Adhikar Andolon Forum president HKS Arefin, general secretary Mejbah Kamal and Adivashi Forum general secretary Sanjib Drang spoke at the discussion. The three CHT districts has five brigades of army of which the government announced on July 29 the pullout of a complete brigade, including three infantry battalions and 35 security camps. The withdrawal will end by next month, the military's press wing Inter-Services Public Relations said in statement. 
